#Drought and Malnutrition Analysis

##Introduction
Africa has the highest rate of malnutrition globally and suffers from severe drought at the same time.
This analysis will look consider different malnutrition indicators such as stunting, underweight and
wasting in children and determine if there is a relationship between malnutrition
and drought and if malnutrition indicators can be classified from different severities of drought and
known malnutrition factors using a logistic regression model. 

##Methodology

###DataSets

####Malnutrition
The child malnutrition data was gathered from DHS and the most recent dataset from each year was
gathered within a 10-year period. Each file was named with the convention of
Country_Child_DHSFileCode_Year.csv. The malnutrition indicators used are from the WHO growth
standards introduced in 2006. From each dataset the standard deviation of Height/Age (Stunting),
Weight/Height (Wasting) and Weight/Age (Underweight) and each malnutrition indicator is defined as
prevalent if standard deviation is two from the median. [1]

####Drought
The drought data was collected from the opensource database Global Drought Monitor. The country was
gathered from the DHS Survey data and the drought data was then gathered for that region. The 
SPEI (Standardized Precipitation Evapotranspiration index) is used to identify the
severity of droughts as the index is used to quantify the precipitation deficit over time and space. A 3-
month index was used, which is a short-term or seasonal drought index, as wasting is mainly the result
of sudden or recent weight loss due to short-term shocks such as drought. Using a 3-month index also
better captures drought events affecting agricultures. Positive values indicate a wet period, while a dry
period has a negative value. The different drought severities used are no drought (value > 0), mild
drought (-1 < value <= 0), moderate drought ( -1.5 < value <= -1) and sever drought (value <= -1.5). [2]

####Features and Encoding
The features used for this analysis were taken from pre-existing knowledge of indicators on malnutrition:
Drought, BMI, Vaccination and Diarrhea. All bolded questions are taken from the textbook Principles of Data Wrangling [3].

**How are the record fields encoded? What are there mapped values?**
The values are encoded according to the DHS Recode Manual.[4] The BMI standard deviation field is encoded
as a numeric value but it has been multiplied by a factor of 100, to get the true value the value must be
divided by 100. This is the same as the malnutrition indicators, which will be the labels, for Weight for
Age, Height for Age and Weight for Height. The Vaccination and Diarrhea are encoded as categorical data where
an integer number represents a category. For Vaccination and Diarrhea category 1 represents whether a child
has been vaccinated and whether a child has had diarrhea lasting longer than two weeks respectively.

####Combining the Datasets

Each child dataset and each drought dataset for the same country was loaded into a spark dataframe for processing. The year the survey was collected was extracted from each dataset to match with the drought data year using the following code:

```scala
val distinctYears = df.select(df("v007")).distinct.rdd.map(r => r(0)).collect()

for(year <- distinctYears){
        var tempDF = temp.filter(temp("DATA").contains(year))
        droughtDF = droughtDF.union(tempDF)
    }
```
This resulted in obtaining the drought data for the corresponding years of the survey. Since we are using a 3 month SPEI index, the only data column that is used is "SPEI_3". For the Drought data to be combined with the Child data, the Date in the drought data
needed to be parsed into month and year and the month needed to be converted to its numerical representation. A Month dataframe was used for this conversion as shown below:

```scala
val Monthdf = Seq(
      ("Jan", 1), ("Feb", 2), ("Mar",3), ("Apr",4), ("May",5), ("Jun",6), ("Jul",7), ("Aug", 8), ("Sep", 9), ("Oct", 10), ("Nov", 11), ("Dec", 12)
      ).toDF("MonthStr", "MonthVal").as("m")
      
droughtDF = droughtDF.withColumn("Year",droughtDF.col("DATA").substr(4,4))
droughtDF = droughtDF.withColumn("Month",droughtDF.col("DATA").substr(0,3))
droughtDF = droughtDF.join(Monthdf,col("MonthStr") === col("Month"), "inner" )
droughtDF = droughtDF.select(droughtDF.col("MonthVal"), droughtDF.col("Year"), droughtDF.col("SPEI_3"))
      
```
The drought data was then joined on the child dataset by month and by year as shown from the sample dataset above. This resulted in a complete dataset for each child the level of drought that was affecting them. [1]

```scala
    var data = df.join(droughtDF, (col("MonthVal") === col("v006")) && (col("Year") === col("v007")), "inner")
```

%md
###Data Cleaning and Scope

Using the data below as reference, the following pre proccessed methods need to be applied to the data for it to be correctly analyzed and interpreted. The following values must be removed from every column:
    1. Null Values
    2. 99, 999, 9999, 99999
    3. 98, 998, 9998, 99998

As per the DHS Recode Manual, for the columns Height_Age, Weight_Age, Weight_Height, BMI_STDEV the value has to be divided by 100 due to the encoding feature described above. 

The data then needs to be split into 3 dataframes, one for wasting, stunting and underweight with the following features: BMI_STDEV, Vaccination, Diarrhea and SPEI_3.

**For the analysis that you want to perform, can you deduce or infer additional relevant characteristics from the ones that you have?**

When transforming the Vaccination column from categorical to binary, if the child has received vaccination for diseases, 1 is the child has received a vaccination for dieseases otherwise 0. For the dirrahea column, if the child has had dirrahea lasting 2 weeks or more which is identified by a 1 or 2 is transformed to 1, otherwise 0.

When transforming the standard deviation of Weight for Age, Height for age and Weight for Height to identify if a child is stunted. If the child is less than -2 standard devations away from the mean they are considered to have malnutrition according to WHO standards. [6]

When transforming the SPEI index to reflect drought the following categories are used:
    1. Mild Drought: SPEI 0 - -1
    2. Moderate Drought: SPEI -1 - -1.5
    3. Extreme Drought: SPEI < -1.5

**Are there multiple records for the same child?**

As this is child data and survey data there is possibility for the same child to appear in the entire dataset more than once in the following possible scenarios:
    1. The child was surveyed in 1 cluster and during the time period in between surveys moved to a different cluster or moved to a different country.
    2. A follow up survey was done 5 years later and the same child was interviewed.
    
From the current dataset the most recent survey from each country is being used and the likelihood of outcome 1 happening is out of our control and not likely to happen. It is concluded that each record in the dataset is a unique child.

When transforming the SPEI index to reflect drought the following categories are used:

1. Mild Drought: SPEI 0 - -1
2. Moderate Drought: SPEI -1 - -1.5
3. Extreme Drought: SPEI < -1.5

Are there multiple records for the same child?

As this is child data and survey data there is possibility for the same child to appear in the entire dataset more than once in the following possible scenarios:

1. The child was surveyed in 1 cluster and during the time period in between surveys moved to a different cluster or moved to a different country.
2. A follow up survey was done 5 years later and the same child was interviewed.

From the current dataset the most recent survey from each country is being used and the likelihood of outcome 1 happening is out of our control and not likely to happen. It is concluded that each record in the dataset is a unique child.

Three logistic regressions will be run, one to predict stunting, wasting and underweight (1 if child is malnourished according to the correponding WHO metric, 0 otherwise). Lastly for Stunting, Wasting and Underweight if their respective WHO indicators are less than -2 standard deviations away from the mean, k they are considered to be malnourished.

The Logistic regression will be validated by using 5 fold cross validation with 90% of the data used for training and 10% of the data used for testing. Ideally the model would be tested using a variety of parameters and the best parameter combination will be used in the model. Due to not using Spark 2.3, the parameters cannot be tested in parallel (a function in Spark 2.3) leading to model training times of over an hour, therefore the model will used fixed industry practice parameters of: alpha = 0.5 which is a balance between Lasso and Ridge Regression [7]. In conclusion, at preliminary stages it does appear that malnutrition indicators can be predicted by drought and other health factors due to promising results in Underweight and Wasting as well as the Chi-Squared tests results proving outcomes were independant of each other and key variables are independant as well.
